content.description: a slanted side with very little to grab on to
content.location: to the right of cheatstone, start before a crevice towards the back of the boulders

content.description: Chimney crack climbing - use that body jam with the foot and arm, and work yourself up. And that top, both sides have holds to top out.
content.location: To the right of the Indian Overhang. You'll see the crack from the front.

content.description: follow the crack all the way up, layback may be required
content.location: the first wall to the left of the overhang

content.description: Self-explanatory title. Getting on the start can be a bit tricky. Once you're off the ground stick to the right side of the arête to top out. If you want to do a variation of the problem ou can traverse to the layback crack to top out.

Start on the obvious jug that is just to the left of the vertical crack that splits the boulder. Proceed to traverse left across the horizontal seam in the rock. After you reach the area where the seam turns the corner go straight up and top out. Happy sends space cadets!!

Start from a nearly sitting position on Indian Overhang. Right hand deep in the cave, left on sloping piece near the outside of the cave. Bump left hand up to juggy slot and use a heel hook around the right side of the rock to make your way up.
start on a rock near the base and reach high for good holds to an easy face and climb through to the top
content.protection: a spotter and possibly a helmet or pad
content.location: the main overhang and most obvious feature, can walk off from top

content.description: Start sitting down with your left hand on the left most jug in the horizontal crack and your right in a slanted crimp near the base of the rock. Use a heel hook to move your right hand into the crack then use another heel hook on the arete to make your way up to a crimp in the middle of the rock. Grab the arete then it’s easy climbing.
content.location: To the right of The Layback.

content.description: Start on the ledge with your left hand and on a crimp near the base of the rock with your right. Move into the horizontal crack then do a dynamic move straight to the top, or use the quarter pad crimp as an intermediary. You cannot use the arete.

A technical traverse on slopey crimps and small footholds. Start with two hands in the large crack and keep moving left. Top out is where the top of the boulder slopes inward a bit, unfortunately right over a bunch of loose rocks. Spotter recommended!
content.protection: 2-3 pads ideally, there are some rocks in the landing zone
content.location: Right of the cheat stone on the blank face, left of The Slope

content.description: Start sitting down to the left of the cheat stone. Put your left hand on the left side of the boulder and your right on a nice hold on the right. Pull yourself up (may require a heel hook) and make your way to the amazing jug in the middle of the rock. You cannot use the cheat stone or it’s pretty much the same as the original problem.

Start sitting down with your hands on two decent crimps. Pull yourself onto the rock then use some small holds to make your way up to the pocket 2/3 of the way up. Hook your finger inside  of it then top out. You cannot use the cheat stone or the jug in the middle of the rock.
content.location: On the cheat stone boulder, left line up the rock.

content.description: Start sitting with your hands on the shelf near the ground. Make your way up to the right to a series of diagonally oriented crimps. Follow them about until you reach a good side pull. Go up and to the left to a crimp, then top out.
content.location: Go around the Layback Boulder to the massive bolder that makes up the cave. You’ll see a hole in the ground and a shelf with chalk on it leading up to a few obvious holds to the top.

content.description: a short fun wall with a built in cheatstone and an incredible jug halfway up
content.location: the right side of the main overhang

climbs.name: "I Sold My Skin To The Devil"

content.description: Problem is located to the left of "the layback". Start with good holds on the horizontal crack, move up and to the left along the sloping arete.
content.location: Left side of the layback boulder

content.description: 3000 year old Indian rockshelter with a couple boulder problems, a great place to practice and just have fun
